{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:19:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2358"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2358"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.01,0.83,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101687"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2358"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2358"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"149"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11524"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43133"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101687"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increasing forgetfulness. She was the CEO of her company but had to step down as she was not able to work efficiently due to progressively worsening memory impairment. She has a medical history of hypertension but is not compliant with her medications. She does not take any regular medications. Further questioning reveals that she also has mild urinary incontinence for the past three months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears generally well. Her blood pressure is 160/90 mmHg, pulse rate 90/min, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. On neurological examination, she has a wide-based shuffling gait. An MRI of the brain is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alzheimer\u0027s disease","Multiple sclerosis","Normal-pressure hydrocephalus","Parkinson\u0027s disease","Vascular dementia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETriad of cognitive impairment, urinary incontinence, and gait instability along with MRI showing ventriculomegaly is consistent with the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal-pressure hydrocephalus (NPH)\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENPH can be idiopathic or secondary to trauma, infections (eg, meningitis), or subarachnoid haemorrhage. Idiopathic NPH usually presents after the age of 60 years. NPH is caused by decreased reabsorption of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) that leads to ventriculomegaly in the long term. Patients typically present with a triad of cognitive impairment, urinary incontinence, and gait instability (wide, shuffling, magnetic gait). This triad can be remembered with the mnemonic \u0022\u003Cstrong\u003EWet, wobbly, and wacky\u003C/strong\u003E\u0022. Imaging with CT or MRI reveals ventriculomegaly out of proportion to the underlying brain atrophy. Large volume CSF removal via lumbar puncture can improve the symptoms, particularly gait impairment (Image). Patients diagnosed with NPH can be treated with a ventriculoperitoneal shunt which would prevent an increased volume of CSF within the ventricles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClassical \u003Cstrong\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E presents with early memory changes and late personality changes. Patients may have age-related urinary incontinence; however, gait instability is not likely to be seen. In addition, brain MRI finding of patients with Alzheimer\u0027s disease is characterized by brain atrophy which can lead to a compensatory increase in ventricular volume (ie, hydrocephalus ex vacuo).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a demyelinating disease that typically presents in young adults with relapsing-remitting neurological symptoms affecting different parts of the central nervous system. While it can cause cognitive impairment, urinary symptoms, and gait disturbances, the pattern of presentation would typically include other neurological deficits such as optic neuritis, sensory disturbances, or motor weakness. MRI findings would show characteristic demyelinating plaques rather than ventriculomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003EParkinson\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E present with rigidity, bradykinesia, and resting tremors. The gait associated with Parkinson\u0027s disease is a hypokinetic festinating gait in which the patient struggles to initiate a movement, takes short steps, and is unable to turn while moving.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVascular dementia\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with a stepwise decline in executive dysfunction and focal neurological deficits. Memory impairment is usually a late presentation. This patient\u0027s gait instability, absence of focal neurological deficits, and a progressive course make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Normal pressure hydrocephalus presents with the clinical triad of cognitive impairment, urinary incontinence, and gait disturbance (often described as \u0027wet, wobbly, and wacky\u0027).","Brain imaging in normal pressure hydrocephalus shows ventriculomegaly out of proportion to cortical atrophy.","Ventriculoperitoneal shunting is the definitive treatment for normal pressure hydrocephalus and can lead to symptom improvement, particularly in gait disturbance."],"references":["Shprecher D, Schwalb J, Kurlan R. Normal pressure hydrocephalus: Diagnosis and treatment. Current Neurology and Neuroscience Reports. 2008;8(5):371-376. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18713572/","Oliveira LM, Nitrini R, Rom\u00e1n GC. Normal-pressure hydrocephalus: A critical review. Dement Neuropsychol. 2019 Apr-Jun;13(2):133-143. doi: 10.1590/1980-57642018dn13-020001. Erratum in: Dement Neuropsychol. 2019 Jul-Sep;13(3):361. doi: 10.1590/1980-57642018dn13-030016. PMID: 31285787; PMCID: PMC6601311. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31285787/","Das JM, Biagioni MC. Normal Pressure Hydrocephalus. [Updated 2023 Jun 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK542247/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2358"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18652"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18653"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18652"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ea637f3e-d109-4c0c-978a-703147ae19f4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ea637f3e-d109-4c0c-978a-703147ae19f4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"18653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18653"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.eme